LGTM
How is moving the bind ip to the server releated to this change?
The test socket never "binds", so where we did the bind needed moved.
gotcha, makes sense

Do you think dispatch based on Adapter class(function overloading) suits better? We can remove all if const expr for adpter based code. Knowing about different types of possible adapters upfront looks complicating the code I feel. Now we are adding cases for testability as well.

> Do you think dispatch based on Adapter class(function overloading) suits better?

What does this mean?  Can you provide some example code for what this dispatch would look like?

As a general rule, I tend to not prefer function overloading, because it makes code search harder.  Compared to just looking at this code, it's pretty clear what it does in all cases.  But I'm open to something if you think there's a better pattern that's less code.

Please see the example for how to handle prepareMutualTls [here]( https://godbolt.org/z/jjvMxM8jf )

You can do the same pattern for all other adapter interfaces.

General Comment is that, we need not include tcp stream, ssl stream and test stream headers in http_connection. It is to follow "open for extension and closed for modification" rule. Right now we are modifying http_connection code for all possible adapters.

I agree that if there were a clean way to do that, we should, but I think a minimal intrusion into the class compared to just not having tests, i'll take the former.

> Please see the example for how to handle prepareMutualTls here

What you wrote looks like a lot more code, using template overloading (not just function overloading) to do what amounts to basically an if statement.

void prepareMutualTls(boost::beast::ssl_stream<T>& adapter)

looks like you missed the template paramter T in your implementation here.

I realize this is a judgement call, but I'm going to say that the if constexpr code is less code, and more clear what's going on.

There is not much code actually. It is just one extra-level of redirection. This is technique used in modern C++ libraries (such as range or sender-receiver) to enable customisation points using static polymorphism. 

I wrote the code just to give you an overall idea.

Please see the update example [here](https://godbolt.org/z/noYsTbT48 ) , Removed one unnecessary If const expr check; 
Yes, readability is depending on the reader. To me, including tcp, ssl ,and test stream headers in http_connection looks a bit more coupled than necessary. 
We can agree to disagree here.
you can ignore my suggestion

it would help significantly if you could post your example to gerrit as a patch on top on this one, and not to godbolt.  That way we can make sure it compiles, and CI will run, and we're not missing some static analysis reason why the code wouldn't work.  posting to godbolt means that that it's more effort to go review.
Sure
do you worry small changes in the http layer will cause this test to fail?

That's kind of the point of having the test.  If we make changes to the core that change the output (like the fact that date hasn't been present for a while), the test should fail.  Unless there was something you'd like to see instead?
I was worried about changes in defaults that would cause this to look flaky, but if that is the intent then party on.

Nothing in this payload is configurable (they're all built from fixed strings), so I'm not sure how changes in defaults would effect anything.  If we get there, we can always make the test aware of whatever config items we use.
Abhilash, you've overridden my patch again with new content.  Please make an effort to understand how git+gerrit works so that you're pushing to your own reviews, and not overriding others.

Ack.
Sorry for that.
